{"id":"1311.5019","submitter":"Luigi Delle Site","authors":"Luigi Delle Site","title":"Levy-Lieb Principle meets Quantum Monte Carlo","comments":"14 pages, 1 figure; To appear in: \"Many-Electron Approaches in\n  Physics, Chemistry and Mathematics: A Multidisciplinary View\", V.Bach and\n  L.Delle Site Eds. Springer (2014)","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/978-3-319-06379-9_20","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We review an approach where the energy functional of Density-Functional\nTheory (DFT) can be determined without empiricism via a Quantum Monte Carlo\n(QMC) procedure. The idea consists of a nested iterative loop where the\nconfigurational space of the electrons in the QMC procedure is determined by a\ntrial oneparticle electron density; this allows then for the determination of a\nfirst guess for the energy functional, which is then in turn used for a DFT\nminimization process. This latter delivers a new electron density and the loop\nis repeated iteratively until convergence is reached and thus the electronic\nstructure of the system determined. In essence, from the applied point of view,\nsuch an approach is a compromise between the large computational cost but high\naccuracy of QMC and the reasonable computational cost but lower accuracy of\nDFT. The proposed approach goes beyond the standard Kohn-Sham method, which is\nthe standard in DFT, and requires neither orbitals nor the a priori\nspecification of the exchange and correlation functional. From the conceptual\npoint of view, the relevant aspect is that the 3N-dimensional wavefunction is\nderived as a function(al) of the three-dimensional electron density, which is\nthe key principle of DFT.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Nov 2013 11:31:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-11-22"}
